{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-template-js","path":"/linux/how-to-update-only-one-service-in-docker-stack","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>If you have two applications and one database in a stack then the <code class=\"language-text\">docker-compose.yml</code> file looks like this</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"yaml\"><pre class=\"language-yaml\"><code class=\"language-yaml\"><span class=\"token key atrule\">version</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"3.3\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"token key atrule\">services</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n  <span class=\"token key atrule\">app1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">image</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> custom<span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span>image<span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span>app1\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">ports</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n      <span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"8000:8000\"</span>\n  <span class=\"token key atrule\">app2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">image</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> custom<span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span>image<span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span>app2\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">ports</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n      <span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"8080:8080\"</span>\n  <span class=\"token key atrule\">db</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">image</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> postgres<span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span><span class=\"token number\">14</span>\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">environment</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n      <span class=\"token key atrule\">POSTGRES_DB</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> mydatabase\n      <span class=\"token key atrule\">POSTGRES_USER</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> myuser\n      <span class=\"token key atrule\">POSTGRES_PASSWORD</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> mypassword\n    <span class=\"token key atrule\">ports</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span>\n      <span class=\"token punctuation\">-</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"5432:5432\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Let's say you have an update only in one application. How do you update the stack? If you run</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">docker</span> stack down my_stack\n<span class=\"token function\">docker</span> build <span class=\"token builtin class-name\">.</span> <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-t</span> my-app\n<span class=\"token function\">docker</span> stack up <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-c</span> docker-compose.yml my_stack</code></pre></div>\n<p>then you are doing everything wrong!</p>\n<p>After building a new image (or pulling it from the registry) you can update only the specific service with this command</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">docker</span> <span class=\"token function\">service</span> update <span class=\"token parameter variable\">--force</span> --update-parallelism <span class=\"token number\">1</span> --update-delay 5s my_stack_app1</code></pre></div>\n<h2 id=\"about-logs\" style=\"position:relative;\">About logs<a href=\"#about-logs\" aria-label=\"about logs permalink\" class=\"with-anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"20\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"20\">\n                <path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3\n                3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3\n                  9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64\n                  1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\">\n                </path>\n                </svg></a></h2>\n<p>Check logs like this</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">docker</span> <span class=\"token function\">service</span> logs <span class=\"token parameter variable\">-f</span> my_stack_app1</code></pre></div>\n<p>Set log rotation by editing <strong>/etc/docker/daemon.json</strong></p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"json\"><pre class=\"language-json\"><code class=\"language-json\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token property\">\"log-driver\"</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"local\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token property\">\"log-opts\"</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token property\">\"max-size\"</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"10m\"</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Reference: <a href=\"https://docs.docker.com/config/containers/logging/local/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external nofollow noopener noreferrer\">https://docs.docker.com/config/containers/logging/local/</a></p>","excerpt":"If you have two applications and one database in a stack then the  file looks like this Let's say you have an update only in one application…","tableOfContents":"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#about-logs\">About logs</a></li>\n</ul>","fields":{"socialcard":"gatsby-plugin-social-card/e1769d12-ec53-5db2-8582-0f58c43a4aed.jpg"},"frontmatter":{"date":"May 09, 2022","published":"May 09, 2022","lastModified":"May 09, 2022","title":"How to update only one service","subtitle":"in docker stack","section":null,"draft":null,"developing":null,"buttonText":null,"buttonLink":null,"secondButtonText":null,"secondButtonLink":null,"featuredImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"showLikes":true,"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/linux/how-to-update-only-one-service-in-docker-stack.md","url":"/linux/how-to-update-only-one-service-in-docker-stack","next":{"excerpt":"System logs can be very useful for troubleshooting issues that occur on the system. So you might want to store logs persistently across…","fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/linux/persistent-logs-in-ubuntu.md","frontmatter":{"title":"Ubuntu persistent logs","date":"2022-05-24T00:00:00.000Z","topic":null,"article":null},"id":"89e14f35-1324-5bf6-9d8c-7aa848425e84"},"previous":{"excerpt":"You can check the major and minor numbers of the CMake version installed on your system using the following command in Bash: The  options…","fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/linux/check-cmake-version-in-bash.md","frontmatter":{"title":"Check CMake version in Bash","date":"2022-05-02T00:00:00.000Z","topic":null,"article":null},"id":"b747c1ae-8a53-5dc2-a23c-e1f5d098fdd8"},"recentArticles":[{"excerpt":"The commands supposed to be simple but there is always confusion if it supposed to be  or . Actually if we on this path let's just setup…","fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/linux/create-new-user.md","frontmatter":{"title":"Create new user in Linux","date":"2025-03-08T00:00:00.000Z","topic":null,"article":null},"id":"1fec8e66-02c4-57dd-ba50-b7890f4e49d3"},{"excerpt